<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,591,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName authority="(Hebard, 1924)" authorityName="Buzzetti &amp; Fontana &amp; Carotti" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Hebard" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[151,530,592,618]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Cohnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andeana" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,345,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Cohnia andeana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hebard, M." box="[360,522,592,618]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" pagination="109 - 248" refId="ref3648" refString="Hebard, M. (1924) Studies in the Dermaptera and Orthoptera of Ecuador. Proceedings of The Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, LXXVI, 109 - 248." type="book chapter" year="1924">Hebard, 1924</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[538,671,591,617]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[538,671,591,617]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[687,755,592,618]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,197,1940]" captionTargetId="figure-34@3.[165,1425,197,1940]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 1: male from Catamayo; 2: habitat of C. andeana in locality Catamayo (Ecuador)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302597/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) was described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[977,1122,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dichopetala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[977,1122,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Dichopetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1192,1249,592,618]" country="Ecuador" name="Loja" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Loja</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1261,1361,592,618]" name="Ecuador" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. Since its description 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buzzetti &amp; Fontana &amp; Carotti" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Hebard" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[328,465,629,654]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Cohnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andeana">
<emphasis box="[328,465,629,654]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">C. andeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been no more collected and it was only mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rehn, J." box="[1172,1325,629,655]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref3835" refString="Rehn, J. (1955) A new Andean Katydid of the genus Dichopetala (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae). Notulae Naturae, 272, 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1955">Rehn (1955)</bibRefCitation>
; being to date known only for 
<typeStatus box="[395,445,666,692]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">type</typeStatus>
material and from 
<typeStatus box="[670,720,666,692]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,591,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buzzetti &amp; Fontana &amp; Carotti" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Hebard" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[198,334,704,729]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Cohnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andeana">
<emphasis box="[198,334,704,729]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">C. andeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was finally collected in two recent expeditions in the neighborhood of 
<collectingRegion box="[1179,1235,704,730]" country="Ecuador" name="Loja" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Loja</collectingRegion>
, in the village of Catamayo, Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[397,494,741,767]" name="Ecuador" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[511,583,741,767]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,197,1940]" captionTargetId="figure-34@3.[165,1425,197,1940]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 1: male from Catamayo; 2: habitat of C. andeana in locality Catamayo (Ecuador)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302597/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="61" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,591,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,778,804]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[487,596,778,804]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–8" captionStartId="4.[150,268,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[185,1397,204,1923]" captionTargetId="figure-51@4.[181,1401,194,1933]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3–8. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 3: male lateral view; 4: female lateral view; 5: male pronotum lateral view; 6: male pronotum dorsal view; 7: female pronotum lateral view; 8: female pronotum dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302599" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302599/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 5–8</figureCitation>
) of both sexes with typical sulcus behind the second third and consequently metazona long less than half of prozona, without humeral sinus. Male cerci (
<figureCitation box="[1262,1426,816,842]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–20" captionStartId="5.[151,272,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetId="figure-78@5.[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–20. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 9: male abdomen tip dorsal; 10: male subgenital plate; 11: male cercus dorsal; 12: male cercus lateral; 13: male cercus tip; 14: female epiproct and cerci; 15: female ovipositor lateral; 16: male abdomen tip dorsal, treated with KOH; 17: female subgenital plate treated with KOH; 18: male titillators dorsal; 19: male titillators lateral; 20: male stridulatory file." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302601" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302601/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 9, 11–13</figureCitation>
) simply tapering to the apex, curved inward in the distal third. Male titillators (
<figureCitation box="[1075,1206,853,879]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–20" captionStartId="5.[151,272,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetId="figure-78@5.[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–20. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 9: male abdomen tip dorsal; 10: male subgenital plate; 11: male cercus dorsal; 12: male cercus lateral; 13: male cercus tip; 14: female epiproct and cerci; 15: female ovipositor lateral; 16: male abdomen tip dorsal, treated with KOH; 17: female subgenital plate treated with KOH; 18: male titillators dorsal; 19: male titillators lateral; 20: male stridulatory file." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302601" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302601/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 18–19</figureCitation>
) toothless and well sclerotized. Genicular lobes unarmed. Female subgenital plate (
<figureCitation box="[922,1057,890,916]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–29" captionStartId="6.[150,270,1509,1533]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-228@6.[151,1436,185,1491]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 21–29. 21, 24, 27. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924) female subgenital plate, idem treated with KOH, male abdomen tip dorsal; 22, 25, 28: Dichopetala mexicana Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878 female subgenital plate, idem treated with KOH, male abdomen tip dorsal; 23, 26, 29: Dichopetala serrifera Rehn &amp; Hebard, 1914 female subgenital plate, idem treated with KOH, male abdomen tip dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302603" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302603/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 21, 24</figureCitation>
) entire, subhexagonal, apically truncated and longitudinally carinated in the middle. Ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[956,1045,928,954]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–20" captionStartId="5.[151,272,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetId="figure-78@5.[151,1436,194,1800]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–20. Cohnia andeana (Hebard, 1924). 9: male abdomen tip dorsal; 10: male subgenital plate; 11: male cercus dorsal; 12: male cercus lateral; 13: male cercus tip; 14: female epiproct and cerci; 15: female ovipositor lateral; 16: male abdomen tip dorsal, treated with KOH; 17: female subgenital plate treated with KOH; 18: male titillators dorsal; 19: male titillators lateral; 20: male stridulatory file." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302601" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302601/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) regularly upward curved in its middle portion with distal half coarsely serrulated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,591,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,432,1002,1028]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Derivatio nominis:</emphasis>
Named after Theodore J. Cohn of Ann Arbour University in 
<collectingCountry box="[1161,1223,1002,1028]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">USA</collectingCountry>
, who inspired our investigations and allowed us to have a wide overview on the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[953,1098,1040,1065]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dichopetala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[953,1098,1040,1065]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Dichopetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="61" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,591,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,361,1077,1103]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Distribution:</emphasis>
Known for 
<typeStatus box="[531,581,1077,1103]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">type</typeStatus>
locality and surroundings in 
<collectingCountry box="[969,1069,1077,1103]" name="Ecuador" pageId="2" pageNumber="61">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. Adopting the biogeographic arrangement of Latin America by 
<bibRefCitation author="Morrone, J. J." box="[568,766,1114,1140]" pageId="2" pageNumber="61" pagination="467 - 494" refId="ref3680" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2006) Biogeographic areas and transition zones of Latin America and the Caribbean Islands based on Panbiogeographyc and Cladistic analyses of the entomofauna. Annual Revue of Entomology, 51, 467 - 494." type="journal article" year="2006">Morrone (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, the genus is Neotropical occurring in the Nortwestern Southamerican Dominio.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
